<TITLE> Nepal Supreme Court orders action against deadly diarrhoea </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KATHMANDU Tue Aug 4, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Nepal's Supreme Court has asked the government to ensure treatment for thousands of people affected by an outbreak of diarrhoea that has caused more than 200 deaths in the Himalayan nation since April. Thousands of people are still suffering from the disease in more than half a dozen districts in west Nepal where the first case was reported more than three months ago. Authorities say they are using mules and helicopters to transport medicines and health workers to remote villages not connected by roads. But critics say the government was slow to respond. Hemanta Rawal, a Supreme Court spokesman, said the apex court asked the government on Monday to take measures to control the disease and inform it about the action taken within two weeks. "This is a directive order to the government which must take effective steps to save the lives of the people," Rawal said. The diarrhoea epidemic is a new headache for the ruling coalition backed by a loose alliance of 22 political parties already grappling with high inflation, scarcity of some essential goods, daily power cuts and lack of public security. The Maoist former rebels, who quit the government in May, are threatening to launch street protests against the government to press it to contain the epidemic quickly. Officials blame use of contaminated water from streams, absence of health workers in remote villages, lack of awareness and basic medicines for the disease. Nepal is one of the world's 14 poorest countries and nearly a third of its 27 million people live on less than a dollar a day and have no access to basic healthcare. Less than 1,500 doctors are working in 100 government hospitals and health centres across the country, according to official figu
